comments.text:
Whatever it is you're building...
If the solution will involve only a small amount of data (personal/workgroup), you can get away with a lot.
But if you want your solution to perform well at scale, you need to take the time to be certain the data model is optimal.
When you make changes to functionality, be sure the tool hasn't added new tables, columns, and indexes without cleaning up those things that are no longer needed. Make sure that it's creating the correct data types for what you intend to do with the data. Look at the queries and examine whether the indexes appear to cover them properly, or if changes are needed for best performance - dropping what's not being used.
I'm a DBA. It's obvious that the AI coding tools are not. They'll get you going, and all will seem well as long as there aren't tons of users and/or complexity of the data model is very low. With more users and more complexity, you'll be better off having a human manage the database.

comments.text: If your doing a greenfield proj it is better to figure out the real world data structure first and spend time initially drafting the database tables, schema, relationships, etc... you can actually invasion many many more features that you didn't think of while your defining the true data structure. You should always model reality to get at objective truth.  If you start with UI your building it based on surface-level interaction rather than the underlying truth of the domain.  dont focus on what screen you want focus on the reality you are modeling.   Once you have the database with an objectively true data structure and objectively true relationships in-tact you can save a lot of time by scaffolding the api.  then you can swagger-gen the client side service layers that makes those api calls. if your using typescript then you have the full benefit of intellisense for the entire api.  Now all you need to do is provide some sample json data returned by the api, and service layer code with your prompt and watch how little time you need to spend on UI.  The LLM will build the UI rapidly and accurately and with less friction, because it understands types, understands data structure, knows the real-world context based on your sample data, and you don't end up with an incoherent database and tangled api logic.   this always happens when you start with screens/UI first it is the root of all technical debt at 90% of companies because BA's think about screens and devs code for screens first because they are following what gets dished out to them,  in this chain of handoffs each role responds to surface-level artifacts instead of anchoring in reality because they wireframe first and skip data modeling entirely

How do i make you to know that the new chat is a continuation of this chat?" The AI will reply with a sentence to use to start the new chat. comments.text:
@username2828you don't need to copy key pointers. When you notice the chat is getting lengthy, and the AI starts delaying in response, not almost instantaneous as you started, know that it is time to move to a new chat. While on the current chat, just say "Here is getting crowded, let's discuss in a new chat but how do I make you know that the new chat is a continuation of this one?"
The AI will give you a sentence to start the new chat, if it doesn't add "do not reset memory", add it yourself to the sentence.

On the new chat, you paste the sentence and you can even start with, "let's continue with [you insert the previous chat title here], all chat has a title. Then continue with the sentence it gave you.

You'll be amazed how all the context will connect without stress.

You can even tell it to give you a run down of the previous chat, to let you know that it understands the old chat.

I've had over 50 chats without losing even one context, all connected. Even if I come back to any of the chat in months time, all context still connects.

comments.text: @YourAverageTechBro Personally I usually go much more fine grained than that. I was just implementing something that required changes to DB service, API, React hooks and the component. Was being greedy and tried to do it in one chat but ended up having bad results with all models as the task got more and more complex. Ended up realizing I was being greedy, rolled back and decided to do it properly, every task on it's own thread and prepare the context beforehand and, what do you know, everything got done in one shot. This is something I run into all the time - The accuracy is far higher when you don't have all the arguments about DB service changes in the context, which also usually includes wrong information or just something that is not relevant anymore. The longer you go, the more fluff there is in the thread to confuse the AI, and the results suffer.
